            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
                <p>
                    The sherd is a small, nearly flat piece. It looks like a fragment of a bigger sherd: ends of hastae can be seen
                    in the breaks. The sherd is crossed by an inscribed straight line slightly below the mid-height of the sherd.
                    (Inv card) Krasotkina, Bilimovich under the direction of I.I. Tolstoy, March 1949:
                    ἡ γλή[νη]
                    [- -]ν δι-
                    οίχο
                    They translate: "Pupil (of an eye).... perish!"
                    διοίχο = διοίχου
                    This restoration makes little sense, and I think it is influenced by Tostoy's tendency (quite clear in his 1949? monograph) to see 
                    dedicatory insriptions and harmful magical inscriptions in fragmentary graffiti.
                    More importantly, it does not correspond to the preserved letters.
                    
                    Above the line that cuts the sherd into two uneven halves.
                    Line 1. The first letter must be a tau: the vertical and right half of the horizontal are clear. The second letter is eta. The third must be a nu,
                    with raised right hasta. The following is either a lambda or alpha, followed by eta with long verticals.
                     [- - ]τὴν ΛΗ[- -]. There are markings below this line of text, but it is impossible to make sense of them, so it is not clear if they form part of the text or not.
                     Below the line.
                     I think the sherd was flipped upside down, and the first line in the second half is the one on the edge of the fragment: 
                     [- - ]ΟΣ Ζ̣Ο[- -]
                     ? ΙΟ̣  Ν  [- -]
                     The first two letters ΟΣ seem certain to me, as such suggest that it is an ending of a word or name. The following vertical has a short horizontal
                     at the bottom suggesting a zeta, followed by a squarish omicron, of the same shape as before the sigma. There appear 
                     to be remains of a letter to the right of omicron and roughly in line. 
                     A long diagonal that stretches from the straight divider line into the space between omicron and sigma is hard to see as a letter stroke. 
To the right of that diagonal, after some space - two letters are written closely together: iota and either a pi or omicron. I opt for the latter because there seems 
to be a rounded stroke that merges with the straight divider line. After some space, another letter in that line appears to be a nu (the extension of the diagonal to rhe 
right beyond the right vertical of nu looks to me like a slip of the writing implement.

What category of text we are dealing with is impossible to say with any degree of certainty. The use of a sherd, small letter
size, four lines of text, the use of a noun in the accusative, a possible substantive ending in -ΟΣ suggest an account or a personal letter/note.
This would be supported by the residential context of find.

                    <!--Архивные данные - Дело Арх. Комм. 1903 г. No. 80
                 Received from Arch Comm in 1906.  -->
                </p>
